{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496387","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496387"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:45:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:45:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1346"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1346","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1346"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.05,0.12,0.67,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1346"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57321"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1346","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1346"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1346"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42780"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"5789"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5466"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6628"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14972"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15115"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42290"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43978"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57321","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57321"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 88-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of severe pain and paraesthesia on the left side of her face. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. There is no facial droop. A red vesicular rash is visible over the left upper part of her face, involving her forehead, upper eyelid, and the tip of her nose. Otoscopic examination is normal. She is provided with simple analgesia.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["GP review in one week","ENT referral","Neurology referral","Ophthalmological assessment","Opioid analgesia"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic signs of herpes zoster (shingles) affecting the ophthalmic division of the trigeminal nerve. The vesicular rash on the tip of the nose, known as Hutchinson\u0027s sign, indicates involvement of the nasociliary nerve. This sign is crucial as it suggests a high risk of ocular involvement in herpes zoster ophthalmicus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOphthalmological assessment\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step. Hutchinson\u0027s sign is associated with a high risk of corneal involvement, which can manifest as herpetic keratitis. Prompt ophthalmological evaluation is essential to diagnose and treat any ocular complications, which, if left untreated, can lead to permanent vision loss.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGP review in one week\u003C/strong\u003E is insufficient management. While follow-up is important, the potential for ocular involvement requires immediate specialist assessment rather than a delayed review.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EENT referral\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated at this stage. The otoscopic examination is normal, and there are no signs suggestive of ear involvement (such as in Ramsay Hunt syndrome).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeurology referral\u003C/strong\u003E is not warranted as there are no signs of neurological disease beyond the expected findings in herpes zoster.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOpioid analgesia\u003C/strong\u003E alone is inappropriate. While pain management is important, it does not address the potential ocular complications. Moreover, simple analgesia has already been provided, and the priority is to prevent vision loss.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to ophthalmological assessment, management should include oral antiviral therapy (e.g., aciclovir), adequate pain control, and patient education about the potential complications of herpes zoster ophthalmicus. The ophthalmologist may prescribe additional treatments such as topical antivirals or steroids depending on their findings.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Hutchinson\u0027s sign (vesicular rash on the tip of the nose) in herpes zoster indicates nasociliary nerve involvement and requires urgent ophthalmological assessment to rule out or treat herpetic keratitis.","Herpes zoster ophthalmicus can lead to severe corneal complications and permanent vision loss if not promptly diagnosed and treated."],"references":["Tuft S. How to manage herpes zoster ophthalmicus Community Eye Health. 2020;33:71\u201372. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7205171/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42780"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1346"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42780","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/42780"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-25T21:55:31+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-25T21:55:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items